{"title":"ChartInstruct: Instruction Tuning for Chart Comprehension and Reasoning","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Chart understanding models are often task-specific, rely on limited chart sources, and lack instruction-following generality, hindering broad real-world chart comprehension and reasoning.","method":"Create ChartInstruct, a large chart-specific instruction-following dataset (~191K instructions over ~71K charts) spanning diverse real-world charts collected from 157 web domains and prior corpora. Use Gemini Pro Vision to extract underlying data tables/titles for web-crawled charts, then generate multi-task instructions with GPT-3.5/GPT-4 (covering summarization, open-ended QA, fact checking, chain-of-thought reasoning with tool use, code generation, and novel GPT-4–distilled tasks). The dataset is shown to be diverse and of generally good quality, and is used to instruction-tune chart models."},{"problem":"General VLMs (e.g., LLaVA with CLIP) are suboptimal for charts and struggle to align chart visual features with LLMs for instruction following.","method":"Design an end-to-end chart VLM by replacing LLaVA’s CLIP with the chart-pretrained UniChart vision encoder and adding an adapter. Train in two stages: (i) an alignment phase that freezes the vision encoder and LLM and fine-tunes only the adapter on chart-to-table and chart summarization to align visual features; (ii) instruction tuning on ChartInstruct with the vision encoder frozen while updating the adapter and LLM (tested with Llama2-7B and Flan-T5-XL-3B). This yields state-of-the-art results on multiple chart benchmarks (e.g., improved OpenCQA and Chart-to-Text) and better adherence to instructions in human evaluation."},{"problem":"For reasoning-intensive chart tasks, directly consuming image features may miss precise data patterns; LLMs benefit from structured, faithful chart data as input.","method":"Introduce a two-step pipeline: first derender the chart image to a textual data table using UniChart, then concatenate the table with the instruction and feed it to an LLM (Llama2 or Flan-T5), skipping any visual alignment. Instruction-tune the LLM on ChartInstruct. This pipeline excels on reasoning-heavy tasks, achieving new state-of-the-art on ChartQA and chart fact-checking; ablations show reasoning-oriented instruction tasks (CoT and coding) are critical to these gains."}]}
